				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><p class=3D"mw-empty=
-elt">
</p>
<div class=3D"shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=
=3D"display:none">Coordinates comprising two distances and an angle</div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Coord_system_CY_1.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https:=
//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/Coord_system_CY_1.svg/2=
50px-Coord_system_CY_1.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"240" height=3D"=
232" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"620" data-file-height=3D"=
600"></a><figcaption>A cylindrical coordinate system with origin <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">O</span>, polar axis <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>, and longitudi=
nal axis <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">L</span>=
. The dot is the point with radial distance <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=
=81</i> =3D 4</span>, angular coordinate <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86<=
/i> =3D 130=C2=B0</span>, and height <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>z</i> =3D 4=
</span>. The reference plane contains the purple section.</figcaption></fig=
ure>
<p>A <b>cylindrical coordinate system</b> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Three-dimensional" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Three-dimens=
ional">three-dimensional</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coord=
inate_system" title=3D"Coordinate system">coordinate system</a> that specif=
ies point positions around a main axis (a chosen <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Directed_line" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Directed line"=
>directed line</a>) and an auxiliary axis (a reference <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ray (ge=
ometry)">ray</a>). The three cylindrical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Coordinates" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Coordinates">coordinates=
</a> are: the point <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perpendicular_=
distance" title=3D"Perpendicular distance">perpendicular distance</a> <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=81</i></span> from the main axis; the point <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signed_distance" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Signed distance">signed distance</a> <i>z</i> along the main axis =
from a chosen <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Origin_(mathematics)=
" title=3D"Origin (mathematics)">origin</a>; and the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_angle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Plane angle"=
>plane angle</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i></span> of the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_projection_on_a_plane" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Vector projection on a plane">point projection</a> on =
a reference plane (passing through the origin and perpendicular to the main=
 axis)=20
</p><p>The main axis is variously called the <i>cylindrical</i> or <i>longi=
tudinal</i> axis. The auxiliary axis is called the <i>polar axis</i>, which=
 lies in the reference plane, starting at the origin, and pointing in the r=
eference direction.
Other directions perpendicular to the longitudinal axis are called <i>radia=
l lines</i>.
</p><p>The distance from the axis may be called the <i>radial distance</i> =
or <i>radius</i>, while the angular coordinate is sometimes referred to as =
the <i>angular position</i> or as the <i>azimuth</i>. The radius and the az=
imuth are together called the <i>polar coordinates</i>, as they correspond =
to a two-dimensional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_coordin=
ates" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polar coordinates">polar coordinate</a=
> system in the plane through the point, parallel to the reference plane. T=
he third coordinate may be called the <i>height</i> or <i>altitude</i> (if =
the reference plane is considered horizontal), <i>longitudinal position</i>=
,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Cylindrical_coordinate_system#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or <i>axial=
 position</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cylindrical_coordinate_system#cite_note-2"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>Cylindrical coordinates are useful in connection with objects and ph=
enomena that have some rotational <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Symmetry" title=3D"Symmetry">symmetry</a> about the longitudinal axis, such=
 as water flow in a straight pipe with round cross-section, heat distributi=
on in a metal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cylinder_(geometry)"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cylinder (geometry)">cylinder</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromagnetic_fields" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Electromagnetic fields">electromagnetic fields</a> produced b=
y an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_current" title=3D"El=
ectric current">electric current</a> in a long, straight wire, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accretion_disk" title=3D"Accretion disk">accre=
tion disks</a> in astronomy, and so on.
</p><p>They are sometimes called <i>cylindrical polar coordinates</i><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Cylindrical_coordinate_system#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or <i>polar cylind=
rical coordinates</i>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cylindrical_coordinate_system#cite_note-4"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> and are sometimes used to specify the position of stars in a gala=
xy (<i>galactocentric cylindrical polar coordinates</i>).<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cylindric=
al_coordinate_system#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCylindrical_coor=
dinate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Def=
inition"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>The three coordinates (<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rho_(letter)" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Rho (letter)">=CF=81</a></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml=
 mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Phi" title=3D"Phi">=CF=86</a></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">z</span>) of a point <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" s=
tyle=3D"font-style:italic;">P</span> are defined as:
</p>
<ul><li>The <i>radial distance</i> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">=CF=81</span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Euclidean_distance" title=3D"Euclidean distance">Euclidean distance</a=
> from the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">z</spa=
n>-axis to the point <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">P</span>.</li>
<li>The <i>azimuth</i> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">=CF=86</span> is the angle between the reference direction on the cho=
sen plane and the line from the origin to the projection of <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">P</span> on the plane.</li>
<li>The <i>axial coordinate</i> or <i>height</i> <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">z</span> is the signed distance from the ch=
osen plane to the point <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">P</span>.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Unique_cylindrical_coordina=
tes">Unique cylindrical coordinates</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DCylindrical_coordinate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp=
;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Unique cylindrical coordinates"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>As in polar coordinates, the same point with cylindrical coordinates <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml">(<i>=CF=81</i>, <i>=CF=86</i>, <i>z</i>)</span> has in=
finitely many equivalent coordinates, namely <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>=
=CF=81</i>, <i>=CF=86</i> =C2=B1 <i>n</i>=C3=97360=C2=B0, <i>z</i>)</span> =
and <span class=3D"texhtml">(=E2=88=92<i>=CF=81</i>, <i>=CF=86</i> =C2=B1 (=
2<i>n</i> + 1)=C3=97180=C2=B0, <i>z</i>),</span> where <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> is any integer. Moreover, if=
 the radius <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=
=81</span> is zero, the azimuth is arbitrary.
</p><p>In situations where someone wants a unique set of coordinates for ea=
ch point, one may restrict the radius to be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Non-negative" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Non-negative">non-ne=
gative</a> (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=81</i> =E2=89=A5 0</span>) and t=
he azimuth <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=86=
</span> to lie in a specific <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inter=
val_(mathematics)" title=3D"Interval (mathematics)">interval</a> spanning 3=
60=C2=B0, such as <span class=3D"texhtml">[=E2=88=92180=C2=B0,+180=C2=B0]</=
span> or <span class=3D"texhtml">[0,360=C2=B0]</span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Conventions">Conventions</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCylindrical_co=
ordinate_system&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: C=
onventions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>The notation for cylindrical coordinates is not uniform. The <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Organization_for_Standardizatio=
n" title=3D"International Organization for Standardization">ISO</a> standar=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_31-11" title=3D"ISO 31-11">3=
1-11</a> recommends <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>=CF=81</i>, <i>=CF=86</i>, =
<i>z</i>)</span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">=CF=81</span> is the radial coordinate, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=86</span> the azimuth, and <span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">z</span> the height. However, t=
he radius is also often denoted <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">r</span> or <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">s</span>, the azimuth by <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">=CE=B8</span> or <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">t</span>, and the third coordinate by <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">h</span> or (if the cylindrical axis=
 is considered horizontal) <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">x</span>, or any context-specific letter.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Cylindrical_coordinate_surfac=
es.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.=
org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b2/Cylindrical_coordinate_surfaces.png/250px-=
Cylindrical_coordinate_surfaces.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" heigh=
t=3D"213" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"680" data-file-heigh=
t=3D"580"></a><figcaption>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coor=
dinate_surfaces" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Coordinate surfaces">coordi=
nate surfaces</a> of the cylindrical coordinates <span class=3D"texhtml">(<=
i>=CF=81</i>, <i>=CF=86</i>, <i>z</i>)</span>. The red <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cylinder_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cy=
linder (geometry)">cylinder</a> shows the points with <span class=3D"texhtm=
l"><i>=CF=81</i> =3D 2</span>, the blue <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Plane_(mathematics)" title=3D"Plane (mathematics)">plane</a> shows th=
e points with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>z</i> =3D 1</span>, and the yellow=
 half-plane shows the points with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=86</i> =3D=
 =E2=88=9260=C2=B0</span>. The <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">z</span>-axis is vertical and the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar=
" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span>-axis is highlighted in green.  The =
three surfaces intersect at the point <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">P</span> with those coordinates (shown as a black sphe=
re); the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartesian_coordinate_syst=
em" title=3D"Cartesian coordinate system">Cartesian coordinates</a> of <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">P</span> are roughly =
(1.0, =E2=88=921.732, 1.0).</figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Cylindrical_coordinate_surfaces.gif" class=3D=
"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/co=
mmons/thumb/5/5e/Cylindrical_coordinate_surfaces.gif/250px-Cylindrical_coor=
dinate_surfaces.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"240" class=
=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"408" data-file-height=3D"391"></a><=
figcaption>Cylindrical coordinate surfaces. The three orthogonal components=
, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=81</span> (=
green), <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=86</s=
pan> (red), and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">z=
</span> (blue), each increasing at a constant rate. The point is at the int=
ersection between the three colored surfaces.</figcaption></figure>
<p>In concrete situations, and in many mathematical illustrations, a positi=
ve angular coordinate is measured <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Clockwise" title=3D"Clockwise">counterclockwise</a> as seen from any point =
with positive height.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Coordinate_system_conversio=
ns">Coordinate system conversions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
